description:
In lichen_l2_enable() enable path (lines 1113-1127):
```c
int ret = lichen_lora_l2_set_rx_callback(lora_rx_callback, NULL);
if (ret != 0) {
    LOG_ERR(...);
#if HAVE_LICHEN_LINK
    if (link_ctx_initialized_here) {
        k_mutex_lock(&tx_mutex, K_FOREVER);
        k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_FOREVER);
        atomic_set(&link_ctx_initialized, 0);
        lichen_link_cleanup(&link_ctx);
        k_mutex_unlock(&rx_mutex);
        k_mutex_unlock(&tx_mutex);
    }
#endif
    return ret;
}
```

The rollback only cleans up link_ctx if it was initialized in THIS call (link_ctx_initialized_here). But it doesn't clear the replay_table that was initialized at line 1101. 

Actually looking at line 1101:
```c
lichen_replay_table_init(&replay_table);
```

This is called only inside the 'if (!atomic_get(&link_ctx_initialized))' block (line 1061), which also sets link_ctx_initialized_here = true (line 1103). So if we enter the rollback, link_ctx_initialized_here is true, and we do the cleanup. The replay_table was also init'd in this case.

But the cleanup doesn't call lichen_replay_table_init() to reset it. Is this a problem? Looking at lichen_replay_table_init(), it's just a memset() - so the table is left in a consistent (initialized) state. The next successful enable() will re-init it anyway at line 1101.

Actually wait - if link_ctx_initialized is set to 0 in the rollback (line 1120), then the next enable() will enter the if block at line 1061 and re-init the replay_table.

NO BUG - the state is consistent after rollback.
